<TITLE> Ban's visit comes at 'significant' time </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 1 (bdnews24.com) - UN secretary-general Ban Ki-moon arrived in Bangladesh Saturday, on a two-day official visit carrying special significance in the backdrop of ensuing elections and the country's present political context. The fourth UN chief to visit Bangladesh, he landed in Dhaka on a special UN plane shortly before 6pm, after visiting neighbouring India and Nepal. Ban will meet president Iajuddin Ahmed, chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed and foreign adviser Iftekhar Ahmed Chowdhury to discuss the country's return to democracy through the Dec 18 general elections. He is also scheduled to meet the leaders of the BNP and the Awami League during his visit. "Both the UN and Bangladesh considers this visit very significant," the foreign adviser told the journalists after welcoming the UN secretary general at Zia International Airport. "Bangladesh plays a special role in UN peacekeeping missions. Bangladesh has also made great strides in social and economic development. The secretary general's visit is in recognition of these." "Ban Ki-moon will hold discussions with our political parties. As we are approaching the national elections, we hope that the UN will assist us," the foreign adviser said. The UN secretary general was driven from the airport to the Sonargaon Hotel under special security arrangements, to hold talks with the foreign affairs adviser. According to his itinerary, Ban will meet the foreign adviser on Saturday evening and attend a dinner hosted by the chief adviser in his honour. On Sunday, he will place a floral wreath at the National Memorial at Savar in the morning and fly to Sirajganj and Bogra to see a UNDP project and a Grameen Bank programme respectively. The secretary-general is scheduled to meet Iajuddin, Fakhruddin and the AL and BNP leaders in the afternoon. Ban, a Korean national, will also attend a dinner at the residence of Korean ambassador in Dhaka during his stay. He will leave Bangladesh on Sunday night, for the UN headquarters in New York, after holding a press conference at the Sonargaon Hotel at 6pm. Previous UN heads that have visited the country were Kurt Waldheim, Javier Perez de Cuellar and Kofi Annan. bdnews
